-------------------------------



Great question ‚Äî this is at the heart of using Microsoft Copilot (or any LLM-powered tool like Researcher, Analyst, or Notebook) effectively.

‚∏ª

üîë Why Prompts Are Important

Prompts are the instructions you give Copilot. They define:
	1.	What you want (the task/output format).
	2.	Where to look (the data sources or pinned docs).
	3.	How to present it (length, style, tone, visuals).

Because Copilot is a generative system, vague prompts = vague or generic output. Specific, structured prompts = high-quality, business-ready results.

Microsoft itself stresses: ‚ÄúWell-crafted prompts are essential to get relevant, reliable, and repeatable results from Copilot‚Äù„Äêmicrosoft.com„Äë.

‚∏ª

‚öñÔ∏è Legal Example ‚Äì Contract Review
	‚Ä¢	Weak Prompt:
‚ÄúSummarise this contract.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Likely Output: A broad overview, may miss critical clause deviations, no risk assessment.
	‚Ä¢	Better Prompt:
‚ÄúCompare Vendor_MSA_proposed.docx vs Template_MSA.docx. Create a 3-column table: Clause, Vendor‚Äôs language, Our standard language. Add a 4th column for Risk (High/Med/Low). Limit to deviations only.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Output: Precise, clause-by-clause deviation analysis with risk categorisation.
	‚Ä¢	Why better: You told Copilot exactly what to compare, how to format, and what to exclude.

‚∏ª

üí∞ Finance Example ‚Äì Variance Analysis
	‚Ä¢	Weak Prompt:
‚ÄúAnalyze Q3 numbers.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Output: Generic summary, e.g., ‚ÄúRevenue is higher, expenses increased, profit fell.‚Äù Not very useful.
	‚Ä¢	Better Prompt:
‚ÄúFrom Q3_actuals.xlsx vs Q3_budget.xlsx, list top 5 cost centers with >5% negative variance. Show variance %, absolute value, and brief potential cause. Create a bar chart of these 5. Then draft 200 words of CFO commentary in a professional tone.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Output: Clear table + chart + narrative commentary you can paste into a board deck.
	‚Ä¢	Why better: You gave data scope, filters, visual request, and tone.

‚∏ª

üìä HR / Workday Example ‚Äì Attrition Analysis
	‚Ä¢	Weak Prompt:
‚ÄúTell me about attrition in HR data.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Output: Generic: ‚ÄúAttrition seems stable; some variation by region.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Better Prompt:
‚ÄúUsing headcount_attrition.xlsx, calculate voluntary vs involuntary attrition for FY24 by region and job level. Highlight functions with >10% voluntary attrition. Create a table and a line chart. End with 3 data-driven recommendations.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Output: Structured insights, with focus on the exact attrition type, drivers, and solutions.

‚∏ª

üîÑ How Prompts Change Quality
	1.	Specificity ‚Üí removes vagueness (focuses on clauses, variances, etc.).
	2.	Structure ‚Üí ensures output format is ready to use (tables, charts, narratives).
	3.	Constraints ‚Üí prevents over-generation (e.g., ‚Äú‚â§200 words‚Äù, ‚Äúuse only pinned docs‚Äù).
	4.	Context ‚Üí makes outputs relevant (‚ÄúCompare against Template‚Äù, ‚ÄúUse pinned Excel‚Äù).
	5.	Tone Guidance ‚Üí ensures the style is right (executive, legal, friendly, concise).

‚∏ª

üí° Prompt Engineering Best Practices
	‚Ä¢	Start broad, then refine (‚ÄúIterative prompting‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	Anchor Copilot with context (‚ÄúUse only pinned docs‚Äù, ‚ÄúLimit to this dataset‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	Always request format (‚Äútable, chart, bullet points‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	Set audience/tone (‚ÄúFor Board deck, 200 words, professional business tone‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	Use constraints (‚ÄúTop 5 only‚Äù, ‚Äú‚â§ 2 pages‚Äù, ‚Äúcite sources‚Äù).

‚∏ª

‚úÖ Bottom line: Prompts are like giving Copilot a job description. A vague job description = inconsistent work. A precise, structured description = focused, high-value, reliable output.

