Here‚Äôs a crisp, role-focused guide to using Microsoft Copilot‚Äôs Researcher, Analyst, and Notebook‚Äîplus how these show up in Workday scenarios. I‚Äôve pulled in the newest official docs and announcements so it‚Äôs practical and current.

What each mode is (in one line)
	‚Ä¢	Researcher: a source-citing agent for multi-step fact-finding across your work graph + the web, returning structured briefs with citations.  Ôøº
	‚Ä¢	Analyst: a data-analysis agent that answers questions about your organizational data (Excel, Power BI / Fabric models, reports) and helps build measures/visuals.  Ôøº
	‚Ä¢	Copilot Notebooks: a scoped workspace where you pin the exact files/chats/notes Copilot can use, then iterate on tasks with tight context control (great for repeatable workflows).  Ôøº

How to open & set up (fast path)
	1.	Microsoft 365 Copilot app (desktop/web): open the app, then in left nav choose Agents ‚Üí Researcher or Analyst. (GA as of June 2025.)  Ôøº
	2.	Notebook: start a Copilot Notebook, attach your Word/Excel/PowerPoint/OneNote/meeting notes; Copilot stays constrained to those references.  Ôøº
	3.	Power BI / Fabric: use Copilot‚Äôs standalone experience to query any report/semantic model you can access (not just the one open).  Ôøº

‚∏ª

Role playbooks & sample prompts

Finance (FP&A, Treasury, IB/Research)

Typical jobs: close pack commentary, variance analysis, board slides, driver trees, KPI QA.

Analyst
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúAnalyze FY25 Q3 actuals vs budget by cost center; list the top 5 variances with root-cause hypotheses and supporting visuals.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Build measures: ‚ÄúCreate a DAX measure for 90-day rolling cash conversion cycle and chart the last 8 quarters.‚Äù
Why it works: Analyst can query connected Excel/Power BI/Fabric models and produce visuals/measures quickly.  Ôøº

Researcher
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúSummarize the latest regulatory capital changes for U.S. banks and potential P&L impacts for mid-caps; include source links.‚Äù  Ôøº

Notebook
	‚Ä¢	Workflow: Pin ‚ÄúQ3 Close.xlsx‚Äù, ‚ÄúBudget v Actuals.pbix‚Äù, ‚ÄúBoardDeck.pptx‚Äù, and ‚ÄúMeeting Notes‚Äù.
	‚Ä¢	Prompt: ‚ÄúDraft the board finance section (4 slides): results snapshot, budget variance, cash flow drivers, outlook. Pull numbers only from the pinned files.‚Äù
Notebook‚Äôs scoped context reduces accidental data leakage and keeps outputs consistent run-to-run.  Ôøº

Tip: If your Excel pulls from Power BI, keep it refreshable so Analyst works on current data.  Ôøº

‚∏ª

Legal (in-house & law-adjacent teams)

Typical jobs: clause comparison, risk summaries, jurisdiction checks, matter briefs.

Researcher
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúPrepare a 1-pager on evolving non-compete rules in California vs. federal trends; cite reliable sources at the end.‚Äù
Researcher returns a structured, source-cited brief and can include your internal memos if you pin them.  Ôøº

Notebook
	‚Ä¢	Workflow: Pin ‚ÄúMaster Services Agreement.docx‚Äù, ‚ÄúVendor-MSA-Redlines.docx‚Äù, and prior negotiation notes.
	‚Ä¢	Prompt: ‚ÄúCompare the two MSAs; list material deviations (indemnity, liability caps, IP ownership), flag risks, and suggest negotiation language based on precedent in pinned notes.‚Äù  Ôøº

Analyst (for ops/legal ops)
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúFrom our matter database export, identify cycle-time bottlenecks and forecast outside counsel costs for Q4; create a chart and a table of top 10 cost drivers.‚Äù  Ôøº

‚∏ª

HR / People Ops (also relevant to Workday users)

Typical jobs: policy Q&A, headcount analytics, attrition insights, talent planning.

Researcher
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúDraft a concise return-to-office policy benchmark from Fortune 500 examples with citations; include pros/cons.‚Äù  Ôøº

Analyst
	‚Ä¢	Ask: ‚ÄúOn our headcount/attrition model, show voluntary attrition YoY by function and location; forecast next quarter and suggest likely drivers.‚Äù  Ôøº

Notebook
	‚Ä¢	Workflow: Pin ‚ÄúHeadcount.xlsx‚Äù, ‚ÄúExit Interview Notes‚Äù, ‚ÄúEngagement Survey deck‚Äù, and ‚ÄúPolicy.docx‚Äù.
	‚Ä¢	Prompt: ‚ÄúGenerate a monthly People Metrics brief: hiring funnel, new-hire ramp, regrettable attrition, diversity trends; include a narrative for SLT.‚Äù  Ôøº

‚∏ª

Using Copilot with Workday (what‚Äôs possible today)
	‚Ä¢	Microsoft provides an Employee Self-Service (ESS) agent pattern with Workday SSO integration. In practice, HR can let employees ask Copilot things like PTO balance, benefits, or policy FAQs‚Äîwhile Copilot routes securely to Workday via configured connectors/SSO.  Ôøº
	‚Ä¢	Agent governance: Workday and Microsoft announced a joint approach so agents you build with Copilot Studio / Azure AI Foundry can be registered in Workday‚Äôs Agent System of Record and tied to Entra Agent ID‚Äîuseful for HR/IT to control identity, scopes, and audit.  Ôøº

HR examples ‚Äúin theory with Workday‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	‚ÄúBook time off for next Friday, then summarize my remaining PTO and link the policy.‚Äù (ESS agent + Workday SSO)  Ôøº
	‚Ä¢	‚ÄúCreate a hiring manager packet for req #2145: include job description, interview loop, and diversity slate progress.‚Äù (Notebook pinned to HR docs + Workday data excerpts)  Ôøº

‚∏ª

Power user tips (efficiency + governance)
	1.	Prefer Notebook for repeatables: Pin the exact sources, then iterate‚ÄîCopilot stays inside that sandbox for consistent, auditable outputs.  Ôøº
	2.	Start with Researcher ‚Üí finish in Notebook: Use Researcher to map the landscape (with citations), then move to Notebook for your team‚Äôs internal packaging.  Ôøº
	3.	Use Analyst‚Äôs standalone experience to query any model/report you can access‚Äînot just the open report. Great for ad-hoc questions during exec reviews.  Ôøº
	4.	Design your semantic models ‚ÄúCopilot-first‚Äù (clear business names, relationships, measures) so Analyst answers are clean and trustworthy.  Ôøº
	5.	Access & rollout: Researcher and Analyst are generally available within Microsoft 365 Copilot; ensure users have licenses and data permissions.  Ôøº

